# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: saint-pierre-and-miquelon
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/1958-french-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in France on 28 September 1958.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/1958-french-constitutional-referendum] Voters were asked whether they approved of the adoption of a constitution for the French Fifth Republic written by Charles de Gaulle.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/1958-french-constitutional-referendum] It was overwhelmingly approved, with 82.6% in favour.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/1958-french-constitutional-referendum] Voter turnout was 84.9% in metropolitan France and 79.8% overall.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/1958-french-constitutional-referendum] The total includes Overseas departments, Algeria, Sahara, Overseas territories (except Guinea, French Togoland, French Cameroon, French New Hebrides and Wallis and Futuna) and French citizens living abroad.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] The **French telephone numbering plan** is used in Metropolitan France, French overseas departments and some overseas collectivities.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Since 1996, Metropolitan France uses a ten-digit closed numbering plan, where the first two digits denote a geographic area, mobile or non-geographic number.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] All geographic numbers are dialed in the ten-digit format, even for local calls.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] The international access code is the International Telecommunication Union's recommended **00**.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] When calling France from abroad, the leading zero should be omitted: for example, to call a number in Southwest France, one would dial +33 5 xx xx xx xx.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Telephone numbers are usually stated as a sequence of five digit-pairs, e.g., 0x xx xx xx xx–and not, for example, 0 xxx-xxx-xxx or others.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Overseas departments and collectivities have distinct country codes and different digit grouping formats.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] The French overseas departments (*départements d'outre mer* or *DOM*) have separate country codes from metropolitan France, with Réunion being assigned the code 262 while Guadeloupe, French Guiana and Martinique were assigned the codes 590, 594 and 596 respectively.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Until 1996, the use of the international access code 19 and country code was required for calls from metropolitan France.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] For example, to call Guadeloupe from metropolitan France, a subscriber would dial 19 590 xxx xxx, 590 being the country code.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] This included the islands of Saint Barthelemy and Saint Martin, which later separated from Guadeloupe to become collectivities, although they still use the same country code.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] By contrast, calls to metropolitan France from the overseas departments only required the use of the trunk code 16.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] However, under the new present French numbering plan, direct dialing was introduced for calls between the DOMs (including *collectivités territoriales*) and metropolitan France, requiring only the '0' to be dialed, with the country code being used as a geographical area code.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Despite this, the 33 country code was not adopted for calls to the DOMs from the rest of the world, because of technical difficulties with operators in neighbouring countries.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] For example, calls to Réunion from Mauritius would have to be routed via metropolitan France, adversely affecting voice quality as well as increasing call costs.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] For many years, French subscribers' telephone numbers consisted of eight digits (including the one-digit area code 1 for all of Paris and its surrounding departments, or a two-digit area code from 20 to 99 for other metropolitan departments; this area code was dialed only after the trunk code 16).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] But that system began to run out of numbers in the 1980s, leading to the adoption of a new "eight-digit" numbering plan on 25 October 1985.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] On that date, France changed to a system of two zones, one for Paris and the surrounding *Île-de-France* and another for the other departments.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Outside Paris, the old area code was incorporated into the subscriber's eight-digit number; for Paris, the area code 1 was retained, and a 4 was prefixed to seven-digit numbers, meaning that a subscriber's number could begin with 40, for example 4056 1873.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] To call the rest of France from Paris, however, the trunk prefix 16 had to be dialed before the eight-digit number.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] On 18 October 1996, this changed to the present "ten-digit" system (including the default one-digit leading trunk code 0), in which each call is dialed using all ten digits, this national scheme being also extended to cover Overseas France in a single area.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Area codes were abolished, and since then France has had a closed numbering plan, where all local or national calls require dialing the leading trunk code.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] For example, Cegetel required subscribers to dial 7; e.g., Paris 71 xx xx xx xx, instead of 01 xx xx xx xx.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Similarly, the international access code using Cegetel would be 70 instead of 00 by replacing the first 0.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Since then, the carrier selection code still exists, but carrier preselection (and number portability) is offered by default on all subscriber lines, and the one-digit carrier selection is rarely used.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Additionally, call fees no longer depend on distance in the French numbering plan, so carrier selection is used only for international calls.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] The national information service reached by dialing "12" was closed in 2005, leading to the creation of numerous new information services reached by dialing 118 xxx.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] They cost €3 per call, plus €3 per minute.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Dialing procedures now reflect ETSI and ITU recommendations.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Until 17 December 1994, Andorra formed part of the French numbering plan, with calls from France requiring the prefix 628, (or 16 628 from Paris).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Those from the rest of the world were made using +33 628, except from Spain, which were made using the prefix 9738.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] On that date, the principality adopted the telephone country code 376.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] Consequently, all calls from France to Andorra had to be dialled in international format, using the prefix 19 376.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] This was later changed to 00 376, along with the second French reform of 1996 to the newer "ten-digit" plan.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/508] On 21 June 1996, Monaco similarly adopted its own telephone country code 377, replacing access from France (33 93).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The first capital of Acadia was established in 1605 as Port-Royal.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Soon after, English forces of Captain Argall, an English ship's captain employed by the Virginia Company of London attacked and burned down the fortified habitation in 1613.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] A new centre for Port-Royal was established nearby, and it remained the longest-serving capital of French Acadia until the British siege of Port Royal in 1710.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] There were six colonial wars in a 74-year period in which British interests tried to capture Acadia, starting with King William's War in 1689.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] French troops from Quebec, Acadians, the Wabanaki Confederacy, and French priests continually raided New England settlements along the border in Maine during these wars.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Acadia was conquered in 1710 during Queen Anne's War, while New Brunswick and much of Maine remained contested territory.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Prince Edward Island (Île Saint-Jean) and Cape Breton (Île Royale) remained under French control, as agreed under Article XIII of the Treaty of Utrecht.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The English took control of Maine by defeating the Wabanaki Confederacy and the French priests during Father Rale's War.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] During King George's War, France and New France made significant attempts to regain mainland Nova Scotia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The British took New Brunswick in Father Le Loutre's War, and they took Île Royale and Île Saint-Jean in 1758 following the French and Indian War.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The territory was eventually divided into British colonies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The term Acadia today refers to regions of North America that are historically associated with the lands, descendants, or culture of the former region.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] It particularly refers to regions of the Maritimes with Acadian roots, language, and culture, primarily in New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, the Magdalen Islands and Prince Edward Island, as well as in Maine.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] "Acadia" can also refer to the Acadian diaspora in southern Louisiana, a region also referred to as Acadiana since the early 1960s.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In the abstract, Acadia refers to the existence of an Acadian culture in any of these regions.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] People living in Acadia are called Acadians, which in Louisiana changed to Cajuns, the more common, rural American, name of Acadians.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Explorer Giovanni da Verrazzano is credited for originating the designation Acadia on his 16th-century map, where he applied the ancient Greek name "Arcadia" to the entire Atlantic coast north of Virginia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] "Arcadia" is derived from the Arcadia region in Greece, which had the extended meanings of "refuge" or "idyllic place".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Henry IV of France chartered a colony south of the St.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Lawrence River between the 40th and 46th parallels in 1603, and he recognized it as *La Cadie*.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Samuel de Champlain fixed its present orthography with the *r* omitted, and cartographer William Francis Ganong has shown its gradual progress northeastwards to its resting place in the Atlantic provinces of Canada.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] As an alternative theory, some historians suggest that the name is derived from the indigenous Canadian Mi'kmaw language, in which Cadie means "fertile land".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The history of Acadia was significantly influenced by the great power conflict between France and England, later Great Britain, that occurred in the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Prior to the arrival of Europeans, the Mi'kmaq had been living in Acadia for at least two to three thousand years.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Early European settlers were French subjects primarily from the Poitou-Charentes and Aquitaine regions of southwestern France, now known as Nouvelle-Aquitaine.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The first French settlement was established by Pierre Dugua de Mons, Governor of Acadia, under the authority of the French King, Henri IV, on Saint Croix Island in 1604.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The following year, the settlement was moved across the Bay of Fundy to Port Royal after a difficult winter on the island and deaths from scurvy.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] There, they constructed a new habitation.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1607, the colony received bad news as Henri IV revoked Sieur de Mons' royal fur monopoly, citing that the income was insufficient to justify supplying the colony further.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Thus recalled, the last of the French left Port Royal in August 1607.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Their allies, the Mi'kmaq, agreed to act as custodians of the settlement.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] When the former lieutenant governor, Jean de Biencourt de Poutrincourt et de Saint-Just, returned in 1610, he found the Port Royal habitation just as it was left.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] During the first 80 years of the French presence in Acadia, there were numerous significant battles as the English, Scottish, and Dutch contested the French for possession of the colony.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] These battles happened at Port Royal, Saint John, Cap de Sable (present-day Port La Tour, Nova Scotia), Jemseg, Castine, and Baleine.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] From the 1680s onward, there were six colonial wars that took place in the region (see the French and Indian Wars as well as Father Rale's War and Father Le Loutre's War).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] These wars were fought between New England and New France, and their respective native allies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The wars were fought on two fronts: the southern border of Acadia, which New France defined as the Kennebec River in southern Maine and in present-day peninsular Nova Scotia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The latter involved preventing the British from taking the capital of Acadia, Port Royal (See Queen Anne's War), establishing themselves at Canso (See Father Rale's War) and founding Halifax (see Father Le Loutre's War).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] From 1640 to 1645, Acadia was plunged into what some historians have described as a civil war.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The war was between Port Royal, where the Governor of Acadia Charles de Menou d'Aulnay de Charnisay was stationed, and present-day Saint John, New Brunswick, where Governor of Acadia Charles de Saint-Étienne de la Tour was stationed.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] There were four major battles in the war, and d'Aulnay ultimately prevailed over La Tour.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] During King Philip's War (1675–78), the governor was absent from Acadia (having first been imprisoned in Boston during the Dutch occupation of Acadia) and Jean-Vincent d'Abbadie de Saint-Castin was established at the capital of Acadia, Pentagouêt.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] From there he worked with the Abenaki of Acadia to raid British settlements migrating over the border of Acadia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] British retaliation included attacking deep into Acadia in the Battle of Port La Tour (1677).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In response to King Philip's War in New England, the native peoples in Acadia joined the Wabanaki Confederacy to form a political and military alliance with New France.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Confederacy remained significant military allies to New France through six wars.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Until the French and Indian War the Wabanaki Confederacy remained the dominant military force in the region.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] There were tensions on the border between New England and Acadia, which New France defined as the Kennebec River in southern Maine.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] English settlers from Massachusetts (whose charter included the Maine area) had expanded their settlements into Acadia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] During King William's War (1688–97), some Acadians, the Wabanaki Confederacy and the French Priests participated in defending Acadia at its border with New England, which New France defined as the Kennebec River in southern Maine.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Toward this end, the members of the Wabanaki Confederacy, on the Saint John River and in other places, joined the New France expedition against present-day Bristol, Maine (the siege of Pemaquid (1689)), Salmon Falls and present-day Portland, Maine.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In response, the New Englanders retaliated by attacking Port Royal and present-day Guysborough.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1694, the Wabanaki Confederacy participated in the Raid on Oyster River at present-day Durham, New Hampshire.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Two years later, New France, led by Pierre Le Moyne d'Iberville, returned and fought a naval battle in the Bay of Fundy before moving on to raid Bristol, Maine, again.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In retaliation, the New Englanders, led by Benjamin Church, engaged in a Raid on Chignecto (1696) and the siege of the Capital of Acadia at Fort Nashwaak.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] At the end of the war England returned the territory to France in the Treaty of Ryswick and the borders of Acadia remained the same.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] During Queen Anne's War, some Acadians, the Wabanaki Confederacy and the French priests participated again in defending Acadia at its border with New England.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] They made numerous raids on New England settlements along the border in the Northeast Coast Campaign and the famous Raid on Deerfield.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In retaliation, Major Benjamin Church went on his fifth and final expedition to Acadia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] He raided present-day Castine, Maine and continued with raids against Grand Pre, Pisiquid, and Chignecto.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] A few years later, defeated in the siege of Pemaquid (1696), Captain March made an unsuccessful siege on the Capital of Acadia, Port Royal (1707).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] British forces were successful with the siege of Port Royal (1710), while the Wabanaki Confederacy were successful in the nearby Battle of Bloody Creek (1711) and continued raids along the Maine frontier.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The 1710 conquest of the Acadian capital of Port Royal during the war was confirmed by the Treaty of Utrecht of 1713.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The British conceded to the French "the island called Cape Breton, as also all others, both in the mouth of the river of St.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Lawrence, and in the gulph of the same name", and "all manner of liberty to fortify any place or places there." The French established a fortress at Louisbourg, Cape Breton, to guard the sea approaches to Quebec.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] On 23 June 1713, the French residents of Nova Scotia were given one year to declare allegiance to Britain or leave the region.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In the meantime, the French signalled their preparedness for future hostilities by beginning the construction of Fortress Louisbourg on Île Royale, now Cape Breton Island.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The British grew increasingly alarmed by the prospect of disloyalty in wartime of the Acadians now under their rule.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] French missionaries worked to maintain the loyalty of Acadians, and to maintain a hold on the mainland part of Acadia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] During the escalation that preceded Dummer's War (1722–1725), some Acadians, the Wabanaki Confederacy and the French priests persisted in defending Acadia, which had been conceded to the British in the Treaty of Utrecht, at its border against New England.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Miꞌkmaq refused to recognize the treaty handing over their land to the English and hostilities resumed.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Miꞌkmaq raided the new fort at Canso, Nova Scotia in 1720.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Confederacy made numerous raids on New England settlements along the border into New England.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Towards the end of January 1722, Governor Samuel Shute chose to launch a punitive expedition against Sébastien Rale, a Jesuit missionary, at Norridgewock.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] This breach of the border of Acadia, which had at any rate been ceded to the British, drew all of the tribes of the Wabanaki Confederacy into the conflict.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Under potential siege by the Confederacy, in May 1722, Lieutenant Governor John Doucett took 22 Miꞌkmaq hostage at Annapolis Royal to prevent the capital from being attacked.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In July 1722, the Abenaki and Miꞌkmaq created a blockade of Annapolis Royal, with the intent of starving the capital.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The natives captured 18 fishing vessels and prisoners from present-day Yarmouth to Canso.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] They also seized prisoners and vessels from the Bay of Fundy.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] As a result of the escalating conflict, Massachusetts Governor Shute officially declared war on 22 July 1722.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The first battle of Father Rale's War happened in the Nova Scotia theatre.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In response to the blockade of Annapolis Royal, at the end of July 1722, New England launched a campaign to end the blockade and retrieve over 86 New England prisoners taken by the natives.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] One of these operations resulted in the Battle at Jeddore.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Then in July 1724 a group of sixty Miꞌkmaq and Wolastoqiyik raided Annapolis Royal.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] As a result of Father Rale's War, present-day central Maine fell again to the British with the defeat of Sébastien Rale at Norridgewock and the subsequent retreat of the native population from the Kennebec and Penobscot rivers.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] King George's War began when the war declarations from Europe reached the French fortress at Louisbourg first, on May 3, 1744, and the forces there wasted little time in beginning hostilities.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Concerned about their overland supply lines to Quebec, they first raided the British fishing port of Canso on May 23, and then organized an attack on Annapolis Royal, then the capital of Nova Scotia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] However, French forces were delayed in departing Louisbourg, and their Miꞌkmaq and Wolastoqey allies decided to attack on their own in early July.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Annapolis had received news of the war declaration, and was somewhat prepared when the Indians began besieging Fort Anne.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Lacking heavy weapons, the Indians withdrew after a few days.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Then, in mid-August, a larger French force arrived before Fort Anne, but was also unable to mount an effective attack or siege against the garrison, which had received supplies and reinforcements from Massachusetts.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1745, British colonial forces conducted the siege of Port Toulouse (St.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Peter's) and then captured Fortress Louisbourg after a siege of six weeks.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] France launched a major expedition to recover Acadia in 1746.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Beset by storms, disease, and finally the death of its commander, the Duc d'Anville, it returned to France in tatters without reaching its objective.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] French officer Jean-Baptiste Nicolas Roch de Ramezay also arrived from Quebec and conducted the Battle at Port-la-Joye on Île Saint-Jean and the Battle of Grand Pré.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Despite the British capture of the Acadian capital in the siege of Port Royal (1710), Nova Scotia remained primarily occupied by Catholic Acadians and Miꞌkmaq.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] To prevent the establishment of Protestant settlements in the region, Miꞌkmaq raided the early British settlements of present-day Shelburne (1715) and Canso (1720).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] A generation later, Father Le Loutre's War began when Edward Cornwallis arrived to establish Halifax with 13 transports on 21 June 1749.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The British quickly began to build other settlements.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] To guard against Miꞌkmaq, Acadian and French attacks on the new Protestant settlements, they erected fortifications in Halifax (Citadel Hill) (1749), Dartmouth (1750), Bedford (Fort Sackville) (1751), Lunenburg (1753) and Lawrencetown (1754).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] There were numerous Miꞌkmaq and Acadian raids on these villages such as the Raid on Dartmouth (1751).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Within 18 months of establishing Halifax, the British also took firm control of peninsular Nova Scotia by building fortifications in all the major Acadian communities: present-day Windsor (Fort Edward, 1750); Grand Pre (Fort Vieux Logis, 1749) and Chignecto (Fort Lawrence, 1750).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] (A British fort already existed at the other major Acadian centre of Annapolis Royal, Nova Scotia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Cobequid remained without a fort.) Numerous Miꞌkmaq and Acadian raids took place against these fortifications, such as the siege of Grand Pre (1749).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In the years after the British conquest, the Acadians refused to swear unconditional oaths of allegiance to the British crown.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] During this time period some Acadians participated in militia operations against the British and maintained vital supply lines to Fortress Louisbourg and Fort Beausejour.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] During the French and Indian War, the British sought to neutralize any military threat Acadians posed and to interrupt the vital supply lines Acadians provided to Louisbourg by deporting them.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] This process began in 1755, after the British captured Fort Beauséjour and began the expulsion of the Acadians with the Bay of Fundy Campaign.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Between six and seven thousand Acadians were expelled from Nova Scotia to the lower British American colonies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Some Acadians eluded capture by fleeing deep into the wilderness or into French-controlled Canada.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Quebec town of L'Acadie (now a sector of Saint-Jean-sur-Richelieu) was founded by expelled Acadians.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] After the siege of Louisbourg (1758), a second wave of the expulsion began with the St.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] John River Campaign, Petitcodiac River Campaign, Gulf of St.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Lawrence Campaign and the Île Saint-Jean Campaign.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Acadians and the Wabanaki Confederacy put up a significant resistance to the British throughout the war.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] They repeatedly raided Canso, Lunenburg, Halifax, Chignecto and into New England.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Any pretense that France might maintain or regain control over the remnants of Acadia came to an end with the fall of Montreal in 1760 and the 1763 Treaty of Paris, which permanently ceded almost all of eastern New France to Britain.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1763, Britain would designate lands west of the Appalachians as the "Indian Reserve", but did not respect Miꞌkmaq title to the Atlantic region, claiming title was obtained from the French.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Miꞌkmaq remain in Acadia to this day.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In Louisiana, the demonym *Acadian* developed into *Cadien*, anglicized as *Cajun,* which was first used as a pejorative term until its later mainstream acceptance.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Britain eventually moderated its policies and allowed Acadians to return to Nova Scotia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] However, most of the fertile former Acadian lands were now occupied by British colonists.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The returning Acadians settled instead in more outlying areas of the original Acadia, such as Cape Breton and the areas which are now New Brunswick and Prince Edward Island.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Among the Acadian descendants in the Canadian Maritime provinces, there was a revival of cultural awareness which is recognized as an Acadian Renaissance, with a struggle for recognition of Acadians as a distinct group starting in the mid-nineteenth century.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Some Acadian deputies were elected to legislative assemblies, starting in 1836 with Simon d'Entremont in Nova Scotia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Several other provincial and federal members followed in New Brunswick and in Prince Edward Island.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] This period saw the founding of Acadian higher educational institutions: the Saint Thomas Seminary from 1854 to 1862 and then Saint Joseph's College from 1864, both in Memramcook, New Brunswick.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] This was followed by the founding of Acadian newspapers: the weekly *Le Moniteur Acadien* in 1867 and the daily *L'Évangéline* in 1887 (fr), named after the epic poem by Longfellow.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In New Brunswick the 1870s saw a struggle against the Common Schools Act of 1871, which imposed a non-denominational school system and forbade religious instruction during school hours.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] This led to widespread Acadian protests and school-tax boycotts, culminating in the 1875 riots in the town of Caraquet.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Finally in 1875 a compromise was reached allowing for some Catholic religious teaching in the schools.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In the 1880s there began a series of Acadian national conventions.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The first in 1881 adopted Assumption Day (Aug.15) as the Acadian national holiday.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The convention favored the argument of the priest Marcel-François Richard (fr) that Acadians are a distinct people which should have a national holiday distinct from that of Quebec (Saint-Jean-Baptiste Day).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The second convention in 1884 adopted other national symbols including the flag of Acadia designed by Marcel-François Richard, and the anthem Ave maris stella.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The third convention in 1890 created the Société nationale L'Assomption to promote the interests of the Acadian people in the Maritimes.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Other Acadian national conventions continued until the fifteenth in 1972.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1885, the author, historian and linguist Pascal Poirier became the first Acadian member of the Senate of Canada.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] By the early twentieth century, some Acadians were chosen for leadership positions in New Brunswick.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1912, Monseigneur Édouard LeBlanc of Nova Scotia was named bishop of Saint John, after a campaign lasting many years to convince the Vatican to appoint an Acadian bishop.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1917, the premier of Prince Edward Island resigned to accept a judicial position, and his Conservative Party chose Aubin-Edmond Arsenault as successor until the next election in 1919.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Arsenault thus became the first Acadian provincial premier of any province in Canada.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1923, Peter Veniot became the first Acadian premier of New Brunswick when he was chosen by the Liberal Party to complete the term of the retiring premier until 1925.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The expansion of Acadian influence in the Catholic church continued in 1936 with the creation of the Archdiocese of Moncton whose first archbishop was Louis-Joseph-Arthur Melanson, and whose Cathédrale Notre-Dame de l’Assomption was completed in 1940.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The new archdiocese was expanded to include new predominantly Acadian dioceses in Bathurst, New Brunswick (1938), in Edmundston (1944) and in Yarmouth, Nova Scotia (1953).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1960, Louis Robichaud became the first Acadian to be elected premier of a Canadian province.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] He was elected premier of New Brunswick in 1960 and served three terms until 1970.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Robichaud government created the Université de Moncton in 1963 as a unilingual French-language university, corresponding to the much older unilingual English-language University of New Brunswick.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1964, two different deputy ministers of education were named to direct English-language and French-language school systems respectively.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In the next few years, the Université de Moncton absorbed the former Saint-Joseph's College, as well as the École Normale (teacher's college) which trained French-speaking teachers for the Acadian schools.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1977, two French-speaking colleges in Northern New Brunswick were transformed into the Edmundston and Shippagan campuses of the Université de Moncton.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The New Brunswick Equal Opportunity program of 1967 introduced reforms of municipal structures, of health care, of education, and of the administration of justice.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In general, these changes tended to reduce economic inequality between regions of the province, and therefore tended to favour the disadvantaged Acadian regions.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The New Brunswick Official Languages Act (1969) declared New Brunswick officially bilingual with English and French having equal status as official languages.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Residents have the right to receive provincial government services in the official language of their choice.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The New Brunswick government of Richard Hatfield (1970–87) cooperated with the Government of Canada in including the right to linguistic equality in the province as a part of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms of 1982, so that it cannot be rescinded by any future provincial government.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Nova Scotia adopted Bill 65 in 1981 to give Acadian schools legal status, and also created a study program including Acadian history and culture.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Acadian schools were placed under separate management in 1996.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Prince Edward Island provided French-language schools in 1980 in areas with a sufficient number of Acadian students, followed by a French-language school commission for the province in 1990.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 2000 a decision of the Supreme Court of Canada obliged the provincial government to build French schools at least in Charlottetown and Summerside, the two largest communities.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The new French-language daily newspaper L'Acadie Nouvelle published in Caraquet appeared in 1984, replacing L’Évangeline which ceased publication in 1982.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The series of Acadian National Conventions from 1881 to 1972 was followed by an Acadian National Orientation Convention in 1979 at Edmundston.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Since 1994, there has been a new series of Acadian World Congresses at five-year intervals starting with 1994 in southeastern New Brunswick and 1999 in Louisiana.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The most recent was centered in Summerside, Prince Edward Island in 2019.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] During much of the 17th and early 18th centuries, Norridgewock on the Kennebec River and Castine at the end of the Penobscot River were the southernmost settlements of Acadia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The French government defined the borders of Acadia as roughly between the 40th and 46th parallels on the Atlantic coast.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The following list includes those who were born in Acadia (yet not necessarily of Acadian ethnicity) or those who became naturalized citizens prior to the fall of the French in the region in 1763.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Those who came for brief periods from other countries are not included (e.g.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] John Gorham, Edward Cornwallis, James Wolfe, Boishébert, etc.).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Acadia was in territory disputed between France and Great Britain.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Although France controlled the territory in the remaining periods, French monarchs consistently neglected Acadia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Civil government under the French regime was held by a series of Governors (see List of governors of Acadia).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The government of New France was in Quebec, but it had only nominal authority over the Acadians.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Acadians implemented village self-rule.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Even after Canada had given up its elected spokesmen, the Acadians continued to demand a say in their own government, as late as 1706 petitioning the monarchy to allow them to elect spokesmen each year by a plurality of voices.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In a sign of his indifference to the colony, Louis XV agreed to their demand.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] This representative assembly was a direct offshoot of a government system that developed out of the seigneurial and church parish imported from Europe.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The seigneurial system was a "set of legal regimes and practices pertaining to local landholding, politics, economics, and jurisprudence." Many of the French governors of Acadia prior to Hector d'Andigné de Grandfontaine held seigneuries in Acadia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] As Seigneur, in addition to the power held as governor, they held the right to grant land, collect their seigneurial rents, and act in judgement over disputes within their domain.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] After Acadia came under direct Royal rule under Grandfontaine the Seigneurs continued to fulfill governance roles.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Acadian seignuerial system came to an end when the British Crown bought the seigneurial rights in the 1730s.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Catholic parish system along with the accompanying parish priest also aided in the development Acadian self-government.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Priests, given their respected position, often assisted the community in representation with the civil government at Port Royal/Annapolis Royal.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Within each parish the Acadians used the elected *marguilliers* (wardens) of the *conseil de fabrique* to administer more than just the churches' affairs in the parishes.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Acadians extended this system to see to the administrative needs of the community in general.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Acadians occupied a borderland region of the British and French empires.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] As such the Acadian homeland was subjected to the ravages of war on numerous occasions.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Through experience the Acadians learned to distrust imperial authorities (British and French).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] This is evidenced in a small way when Acadians were uncooperative with census takers.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Administrators complained of constant in-fighting among the population, which filed many petty civil suits with colonial magistrates.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Most of these were over boundary lines, as the Acadians were very quick to protect their new lands.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] After 1710, the British military administration continued to utilize the deputy system the Acadians had developed under French colonial rule.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Prior to 1732 the deputies were appointed by the governor from men in the districts of Acadian families "as ancientest and most considerable in Lands & possessions,".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] This appears to be in contravention of various British penal laws which made it nearly impossible for Roman Catholics and Protestant recusants to hold military and government positions.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The need for effective administration and communication in many of the British colonies trumped the laws.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1732, the governance institution was formalized.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Under the formalized system the colony was divided into eight districts.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Annually on October 11 free elections were to take place where each district, depending on its size, was to elect two, three, or four deputies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In observance of the Lord's Day, if October 11 fell on a Sunday the elections were to take place on the immediately following Monday.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Notice of the annual election was to be given in all districts thirty days before the election date.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Immediately following election, deputies, both outgoing and incoming, were to report to Annapolis Royal to receive the governor's approval and instructions.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Prior to 1732 deputies had complained about the time and expense of holding office and carrying out their duties.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Under the new elected deputy system each district was to provide for the expenses of their elected deputies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In addition to deputies, several other public positions existed.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Each district had a clerk who worked closely with the deputies and under his duties recorded the records and orders of government, deeds and conveyances, and kept other public records.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] With the rapid expansion of the Acadian populace, there was also a growing number of cattle and sheep.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The burgeoning herds and flocks, often free-ranging, necessitated the creation of the position of Overseer of Flocks.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] These individuals controlled where the flocks grazed, settled disputes and recorded the names of individuals slaughtering animals to ensure proper ownership.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Skins and hides were inspected for brands.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] After the purchase by the British Crown of the seigniorial rights in Acadia, various rents and fees were due to the Crown.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In the Minas, Piziquid and Cobequid Districts the seigniorial fees were collected by the "Collector & Receiver of All His Majesty's Quit Rents, Dues, or Revenues".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Collector was to keep a record of all rents and other fees collected, submit the rents to Annapolis Royal, and retain fifteen percent to cover his expenses.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Before 1654, trading companies and patent holders concerned with fishing recruited men in France to come to Acadia to work at the commercial outposts.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The original Acadian population was a small number of indentured servants and soldiers brought by the fur-trading companies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Gradually, fishermen began settling in the area as well, rather than return to France with the seasonal fishing fleet.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The majority of the recruiting took place at La Rochelle.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Between 1653 and 1654, 104 men were recruited at La Rochelle.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Of these, 31% were builders, 15% were soldiers and sailors, 8% were food preparers, 6.7% were farm workers, and an additional 6.7% worked in the clothing trades.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Fifty-five percent of Acadia's first families came from western and southwestern France, primarily from Poitou, Aquitaine, Angoumois, and Saintonge.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Over 85% of these (47% of the total), were former residents of the La Chaussée area of Poitou.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Many of the families who arrived in 1632 with Isaac de Razilly shared some blood ties; those not related by blood shared cultural ties with the others.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The number of original immigrants was very small, and only about 100 surnames existed within the Acadian community.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Many of the earliest French settlers in Acadia intermarried with the local Mi'kmaq tribe.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] A Parisian lawyer, Marc Lescarbot, who spent just over a year in Acadia, arriving in May 1606, described the Micmac as having "courage, fidelity, generosity, and humanity, and their hospitality is so innate and praiseworthy that they receive among them every man who is not an enemy.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Most of the immigrants to Acadia were poor peasants in France, making them social equals in this new context.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Unlike the French colonists in Canada and the early English colonies in Plymouth and Jamestown, Acadians maintained an extended kinship system, and the large extended families assisted in building homes and barns, as well as cultivating and harvesting crops.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] They also relied on interfamily cooperation to accomplish community goals, such as building dikes to reclaim tidal marshes.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Marriages were generally not love matches but were arranged for economic or social reasons.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Parental consent was required for anyone under 25 who wished to marry, and both the mother's and father's consent was recorded in the marriage deed.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Divorce was not permitted in New France, and annulments were almost impossible to get.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Legal separation was offered as an option but was seldom used.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Acadians were suspicious of outsiders and on occasion did not readily cooperate with census takers.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The first reliable population figures for the area came with the census of 1671, which noted fewer than 450 people.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] By 1714, the Acadian population had expanded to 2,528 individuals, mostly from natural increase rather than immigration.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Most Acadian women in the 18th century gave birth to living children an average of eleven times.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Although these numbers are identical to those in Canada, 75% of Acadian children reached adulthood, many more than in other parts of New France.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The isolation of the Acadian communities meant the people were not exposed to many of the imported epidemics, allowing the children to remain healthier.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1714, a few Acadian families emigrated to Île Royale.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] But for the majority of Acadians, they could not be enticed by the French government to abandon their family lands for an area which was unknown and uncultivated.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Some Acadians migrated to nearby Île Saint-Jean (now Prince Edward Island) to take advantage of the fertile cropland.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In 1732, the island had 347 settlers but within 25 years its population had expanded to 5000 Europeans.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Much of the population surge on Île Saint-Jean took place in the 1750s, as Acadians left during the rising tensions on peninsular Nova Scotia after the settlement of Halifax in 1749.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Le Loutre played a role in these removals through acts of encouragement and threats.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The exodus to Île Saint-Jean became a flood with refugees fleeing British-held territory after the initial expulsions of 1755.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In contemporary Atlantic Canada, it is estimated that there are 300,000 French-speaking Acadians.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In addition, there is a diaspora of over three million Acadian descendants in the world, primarily in the United States, in Canada outside the Atlantic region, and in France.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Most Acadian households were self-sufficient, with families engaged in subsistence farming only for a few years while they established their farms.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Very rapidly the Acadians established productive farms that yielded surplus crops that allowed them to trade with both Boston and Louisbourg.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Farms tended to remain small plots of land worked by individual families rather than slave labor.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The highly productive dyked marshlands and cleared uplands produced an abundance of fodder that supported significant production of cows, sheep and pigs.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Farmers grew various grains: wheat, oats, barley, hops and rye; vegetables: peas, cabbage, turnips, onions, carrots, chives, shallots, asparagus, parsnips and beets; fruit: apples, pears, cherries, plums, raspberry and white strawberry.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] In addition they grew crops of hemp and flax for the production of cloth, rope, etc.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] From the rivers, estuaries and seas they harvested shad, smelts, gaspereau, cod, salmon, bass, etc., utilizing fish traps in the rivers, weirs in the inter-tidal zone and from the sea with lines and nets from their boats.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Charles Morris observed the Acadians at Minas hunting beluga whales.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The Acadians also varied their diets by hunting for moose, hare, ducks and geese, and pigeon.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] After 1630, the Acadians began to build dikes and drain the sea marsh above Port Royal.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The high salinity of the reclaimed coastal marshland meant that the land would need to sit for three years after it was drained before it could be cultivated.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] The land reclamation techniques that were used closely resembled the enclosures near La Rochelle that helped make solar salt.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] As time progressed, the Acadian agriculture improved, and Acadians traded with the British colonies in New England to gain ironware, fine cloth, rum, and salt.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] During the French administration of Acadia, this trade was illegal, but it did not stop some English traders from establishing small stores in Port Royal.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Under English rule, the Acadians traded with New England and often smuggled their excess food to Boston merchants waiting at Baie Verte for transshipment to the French at Louisbourg on Cape Breton Island.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Many adult sons who did not inherit land from their parents settled on adjacent vacant lands to remain close to their families.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] As the Acadian population expanded and available land became limited around Port Royal, new settlements took root to the northeast, in the Upper Bay of Fundy, including Mines, Pisiquid, and Beaubassin.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/acadia] Many of the pioneers into that area persuaded some of their relatives to accompany them, and most of the frontier settlements contained only five to ten interrelated family units.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Adélie Land has borders with the Australian Antarctic Territory both on the east and on the west, namely on Clarie Land (part of Wilkes Land) in the west, and George V Land in the east.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Additionally, it is the only territory claimed within French Southern and Antarctic Lands that is not an island.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Its total land area, mostly covered with glaciers, is estimated to be 432,000 square kilometres (167,000 sq mi).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] The coast of Adélie Land is known for its katabatic winds which push snow and sea ice away from the coast.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] In a 1915 Science Magazine volume, it was named the "stormiest spot on the face of earth".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] The coast of Adélie Land was discovered in January 1840 by the French explorer Jules Dumont d'Urville (1790–1842) who named it after his wife, Adèle.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] This is the basis of the French claim to this Antarctic land.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] The first French research station, Port Martin, was built in 1950.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] It was destroyed by a fire in 1952, and replaced by Dumont d'Urville Station in 1956.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Charcot Station was a French inland base built which was occupied from 1957 to 1960.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Cap Prud'Homme Camp, an Italian-French base, opened in 1994.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Prud'Homme and Dumont d'Urville are the only currently remaining active stations.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] The site of Port Martin was discovered during a French Antarctic Expedition under André-Frank Liotard on 18 January 1950.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Port Martin housed a winter population of 11 in 1950–51 and 17 in 1951–52.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] A crew under Mario Marret built a temporary secondary base in January 1952: Base Marret on Petrel Island.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Port Martin was destroyed by a fire during the night of 23–24 January 1952.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] All of the inhabitants were safely evacuated, and they overwintered at Base Marret.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Only the ancillary buildings of Port Martin were not destroyed by the fire and they have remained mostly untouched since.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] The station is 4,815 square metres (51,830 sq ft) large and houses a summer population of 120 and a winter population of around 30.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] It was built on 12 January 1956 for the International Geophysical Year of 1957–58.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Initially intended to be a temporary station, it was expanded and continually occupied.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Like Base Marret, the station is located on Petrel Island, which is 5 kilometres (3.1 mi) from the mainland.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] The station's research includes ecology, marine biology, glaciology, meteorology and more.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] In the documentary, *March of the Penguins* (2005), Dumont d'Urville Station was the main filming location.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Charcot Station was a French inland base located on the Antarctic ice sheet at 320 kilometres (200 mi) from the coast and from Dumont d'Urville Station, at an elevation of about 2,400 metres (7,900 ft).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] The station, built for the International Geophysical Year of 1957–58, paid homage to Jean-Baptiste Charcot), and was occupied from January 1957 through 1960 housing solely three men.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] The base was composed of a main body of 24 square metres (260 sq ft) (the "barrack") which consisted of semi-cylindrical sections of sheet metal assembled end to end.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] This form was planned to best withstand the snow pressure accumulated on it.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Horizontal galleries were connected to house scientific measurement devices, while a vertical air conduit opened a few metres above the snow level provided ventilation.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] All the supplies and equipment for the Italian-French Concordia Station are transported by a combined convoy of up to seven Caterpillar tractors from Cap Prud'Homme, with Kässbohrer trailblazers and a team of up to nine people; each convoy transports an average of 150 tons of payload.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Part of the Pointe Géologie Archipelago in Adélie Land is protected by the Antarctic Specially Protected Area 120.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] In 2016, a study predicted that an Adélie penguin colony located in Cape Dennison in Commonwealth Bay might be subject to extinction.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] In 2010, a fallen glacier blocked the flow of a river and caused sea ice to overflow to the rocky surface that Adélie penguins require to nest.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Before 2017, an estimated 18,000 pairs of Adélie penguin resided in the Adélie Land.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] However, in 2017, an insurgence of sea ice forced the penguins to travel further to reach the sea.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] Due to this, nearly all of the newborn penguins had died of starvation and exhaustion.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/adélie-land] The Dumont d'Urville Station is in proximity to Adélie penguins, emperor penguins, and seals.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The earliest experimental AM transmissions began in the early 1900s.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However, widespread AM broadcasting was not established until the 1920s, following the development of vacuum tube receivers and transmitters.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] AM radio remained the dominant method of broadcasting for the next 30 years, a period called the "Golden Age of Radio", until television broadcasting became widespread in the 1950s and received much of the programming previously carried by radio.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Later, AM radio's audiences declined greatly due to competition from FM radio, digital radio, satellite radio, Internet radio, music streaming services, and podcasting.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Thus, AM broadcasters tend to specialize in spoken-word formats, such as talk radio, all-news radio and sports radio, with music formats primarily for FM and digital stations.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] — Red Barber, *The Broadcasters*, 1970, pp.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In October 1898, a London publication, *The Electrician*, noted that "there are rare cases where, as Dr. [Oliver] Lodge once expressed it, it might be advantageous to 'shout' the message, spreading it broadcast to receivers in all directions".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However, it was recognized that this would involve significant financial issues, as that same year *The Electrician* also commented "did not Prof.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] On January 1, 1902, Nathan Stubblefield gave a short-range "wireless telephone" demonstration, that included simultaneously broadcasting speech and music to seven locations throughout Murray, Kentucky.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The earliest public radiotelegraph broadcasts were provided as government services, beginning with daily time signals inaugurated on January 1, 1905, by a number of U.S.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In Europe, signals transmitted from a station located on the Eiffel Tower were received throughout much of Europe.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In both the United States and France this led to a small market of receiver lines geared for jewelers who needed accurate time to set their clocks, including the Ondophone in France, and the De Forest RS-100 Jewelers Time Receiver in the United States.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The ability to pick up time signal broadcasts, in addition to Morse code weather reports and news summaries, also attracted the interest of amateur radio enthusiasts.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] It was immediately recognized that, much like the telegraph had preceded the invention of the telephone, the ability to make audio radio transmissions would be a significant technical advance.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Despite this knowledge, it still took two decades to perfect the technology needed to make quality audio transmissions.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In addition, the telephone had rarely been used for distributing entertainment, outside of a few "telephone newspaper" systems, most of which were established in Europe, beginning with the Paris Théâtrophone.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] With this in mind, most early radiotelephone development envisioned that the device would be more profitably developed as a "wireless telephone" for personal communication, or for providing links where regular telephone lines could not be run, rather than for the uncertain finances of broadcasting.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The person generally credited as the primary early developer of AM technology is Canadian-born inventor Reginald Fessenden.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The original spark-gap radio transmitters were impractical for transmitting audio, since they produced discontinuous pulses known as "damped waves".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Fessenden realized that what was needed was a new type of radio transmitter that produced steady "undamped" (better known as "continuous wave") signals, which could then be "modulated" to reflect the sounds being transmitted.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Fessenden's basic approach was disclosed in U.S.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Patent 706,737, which he applied for on May 29, 1901, and was issued the next year.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] It called for the use of a high-speed alternator (referred to as "an alternating-current dynamo") that generated "pure sine waves" and produced "a continuous train of radiant waves of substantially uniform strength", or, in modern terminology, a continuous-wave (CW) transmitter.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Fessenden began his research on audio transmissions while doing developmental work for the United States Weather Service on Cobb Island, Maryland.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Because he did not yet have a continuous-wave transmitter, initially he worked with an experimental "high-frequency spark" transmitter, taking advantage of the fact that the higher the spark rate, the closer a spark-gap transmission comes to producing continuous waves.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] He later reported that, in the fall of 1900, he successfully transmitted speech over a distance of about 1.6 kilometers (one mile), which appears to have been the first successful audio transmission using radio signals.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However, at this time the sound was far too distorted to be commercially practical.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] For a time he continued working with more sophisticated high-frequency spark transmitters, including versions that used compressed air, which began to take on some of the characteristics of arc-transmitters.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Fessenden attempted to sell this form of radiotelephone for point-to-point communication, but was unsuccessful.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Fessenden's work with high-frequency spark transmissions was only a temporary measure.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The next step, adopted from standard wire-telephone practice, was to insert a simple carbon microphone into the transmission line, to modulate the carrier wave signal to produce AM audio transmissions.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However, it would take many years of expensive development before even a prototype alternator-transmitter would be ready, and a few years beyond that for high-power versions to become available.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Fessenden worked with General Electric's (GE) Ernst F.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Alexanderson, who in August 1906, delivered an improved model which operated at a transmitting frequency of approximately 50 kHz, although at low power.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The alternator-transmitter achieved the goal of transmitting quality audio signals, but the lack of any way to amplify the signals meant they were somewhat weak.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] On December 21, 1906, Fessenden made an extensive demonstration of the new alternator-transmitter at Brant Rock, Massachusetts, showing its utility for point-to-point wireless telephony, including interconnecting his stations to the wire telephone network.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] As part of the demonstration, speech was transmitted 18 kilometers (11 miles) to a listening site at Plymouth, Massachusetts.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Because there was no way to amplify electrical currents at this time, modulation was usually accomplished by a carbon microphone inserted directly in the antenna wire.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] This meant that the full transmitter power flowed through the microphone, and even using water cooling, the power handling ability of the microphones severely limited the power of the transmissions.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Ultimately only a small number of large and powerful Alexanderson alternators would be developed.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However, they would be almost exclusively used for long-range radiotelegraph communication, and occasionally for radiotelephone experimentation, but were never used for general broadcasting.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Almost all of the continuous wave AM transmissions made prior to 1915 were made by versions of the arc converter transmitter, which had been initially developed by Valdemar Poulsen in 1903.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Arc transmitters worked by producing a pulsating electrical arc in an enclosed hydrogen atmosphere.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] They were much more compact than alternator transmitters, and could operate on somewhat higher transmitting frequencies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However, they suffered from some of the same deficiencies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The lack of any means to amplify electrical currents meant that, like the alternator transmitters, modulation was usually accomplished by a microphone inserted directly in the antenna wire, which again resulted in overheating issues, even with the use of water-cooled microphones.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Thus, transmitter powers tended to be limited.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The arc was also somewhat unstable, which reduced audio quality.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Experimenters who used arc transmitters for their radiotelephone research included Ernst Ruhmer, Quirino Majorana, Charles "Doc" Herrold, and Lee de Forest.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Advances in vacuum tube technology (called "valves" in British usage), especially after around 1915, revolutionized radio technology.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Vacuum tube devices could be used to amplify electrical currents, which overcame the overheating issues of needing to insert microphones directly in the transmission antenna circuit.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Vacuum tube transmitters also provided high-quality AM signals, and could operate on higher transmitting frequencies than alternator and arc transmitters.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Vacuum tubes remained the central technology of radio for 40 years, until transistors began to dominate in the late 1950s, and are still used in the highest power broadcast transmitters.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Unlike telegraph and telephone systems, which used completely different types of equipment, most radio receivers were equally suitable for both radiotelegraph and radiotelephone reception.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In 1903 and 1904, the electrolytic detector and thermionic diode (Fleming valve) were invented by Reginald Fessenden and John Ambrose Fleming, respectively.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Most important, in 1904–1906, the crystal detector, the simplest and cheapest AM detector, was developed by G.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Homemade crystal radios spread rapidly during the next 15 years, providing ready audiences for the first radio broadcasts.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] One limitation of crystals sets was the lack of amplifying the signals, so listeners had to use earphones, and it required the development of vacuum-tube receivers before loudspeakers could be used.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The dynamic cone loudspeaker, invented in 1924, greatly improved audio frequency response over the previous horn speakers, allowing music to be reproduced with good fidelity.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] AM radio offered the highest sound quality available in a home audio device prior to the introduction of the high-fidelity, long-playing record in the late 1940s.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Listening habits changed in the 1960s due to the introduction of the revolutionary transistor radio (Regency TR-1, the first transistor radio released December 1954), which was made possible by the invention of the transistor in 1948.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] (The transistor was invented at Bell labs and released in June 1948.) Their compact size — small enough to fit in a shirt pocket — and lower power requirements, compared to vacuum tubes, meant that for the first time radio receivers were readily portable.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The transistor radio became the most widely used communication device in history, with billions manufactured by the 1970s.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Radio became a ubiquitous "companion medium" which people could take with them anywhere they went.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The demarcation between what is considered "experimental" and "organized" broadcasting is largely arbitrary.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Following World War I, the number of stations providing a regular broadcasting service greatly increased, primarily due to advances in vacuum-tube technology.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However, there were numerous cases of entertainment broadcasts being presented on a regular schedule before their formal recognition by government regulators.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Because most longwave radio frequencies were used for international radiotelegraph communication, a majority of early broadcasting stations operated on mediumwave frequencies, whose limited range generally restricted them to local audiences.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] One method for overcoming this limitation, as well as a method for sharing program costs, was to create radio networks, linking stations together with telephone lines to provide a nationwide audience.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In the U.S., the American Telephone and Telegraph Company (AT&T) was the first organization to create a radio network, and also to promote commercial advertising, which it called "toll" broadcasting.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Its flagship station, WEAF (now WFAN) in New York City, sold blocks of airtime to commercial sponsors that developed entertainment shows containing commercial messages.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] AT&T held a monopoly on quality telephone lines, and by 1924 had linked 12 stations in Eastern cities into a "chain".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The Radio Corporation of America (RCA), General Electric, and Westinghouse organized a competing network around its own flagship station, RCA's WJZ (now WABC) in New York City, but were hampered by AT&T's refusal to lease connecting lines or allow them to sell airtime.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In 1926, AT&T sold its radio operations to RCA, which used them to form the nucleus of the new NBC network.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] By the 1930s, most of the major radio stations in the country were affiliated with networks owned by two companies, NBC and CBS.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In 1934, a third national network, the Mutual Radio Network, was formed as a cooperative owned by its stations.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] A second country which quickly adopted network programming was the United Kingdom, and its national network quickly became a prototype for a state-managed monopoly of broadcasting.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] A rising interest in radio broadcasting by the British public pressured the government to reintroduce the service, following its suspension in 1920.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However, the government also wanted to avoid what it termed the "chaotic" U.S. experience of allowing large numbers of stations to operate with few restrictions.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] There were also concerns about broadcasting becoming dominated by the Marconi company.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Arrangements were made for six large radio manufacturers to form a consortium, the British Broadcasting Company (BBC), established on October 18, 1922, which was given a monopoly on broadcasting.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] This enterprise was supported by a tax on radio sets sales, plus an annual license fee on receivers, collected by the Post Office.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Initially the eight stations were allowed regional autonomy.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In 1927, the original broadcasting organization was replaced by a government chartered British Broadcasting Corporation. an independent nonprofit supported solely by a 10 shilling receiver license fee.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Both highbrow and mass-appeal programs were carried by the National and Regional networks.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The period from the early 1920s through the 1940s is often called the "Golden Age of Radio".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] During this period AM radio was the main source of home entertainment, until it was replaced by television.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] For the first time entertainment was provided from outside the home, replacing traditional forms of entertainment such as oral storytelling and music from family members.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] New forms were created, including radio plays, mystery serials, soap operas, quiz shows, variety hours, situation comedies and children's shows.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Radio news, including remote reporting, allowed listeners to be vicariously present at notable events.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Radio greatly eased the isolation of rural life.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Political officials could now speak directly to millions of citizens.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] One of the first to take advantage of this was American president Franklin Roosevelt, who became famous for his fireside chats during the Great Depression.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However, broadcasting also provided the means to use propaganda as a powerful government tool, and contributed to the rise of fascist and communist ideologies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In the 1940s, two new broadcast media, FM radio and television, began to provide extensive competition with the established broadcasting services.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The AM radio industry suffered a serious loss of audience and advertising revenue, and coped by developing new strategies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Instead of live music, most stations began playing less expensive recorded music.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In the late 1960s and 1970s, top 40 rock and roll stations in the U.S. and Canada such as WABC and CHUM transmitted highly processed and extended audio to 11 kHz, successfully attracting huge audiences.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In the late 1970s, spurred by the exodus of musical programming to FM stations, the AM radio industry in the United States developed technology for broadcasting in stereo.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Other nations adopted AM stereo, most commonly choosing Motorola's C-QUAM, and in 1993, the United States also made the C-QUAM system its standard, after a period allowing four different standards to compete.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The selection of a single standard improved acceptance of AM stereo, however overall there was limited adoption of AM stereo worldwide, and interest declined after 1990.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] With the continued migration of AM stations away from music to news, sports, and talk formats, receiver manufacturers saw little reason to adopt the more expensive stereo tuners, and thus radio stations have little incentive to upgrade to stereo transmission.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] This sometimes results in the sale of the transmitter site, with the station relocating to a more distant shared site using significantly less power, or completely shutting down operations.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The ongoing development of alternative transmission systems, including DAB, satellite radio, and HD radio, continued the decline of the popularity of the traditional broadcast technologies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] These new options, including the introduction of Internet streaming, particularly resulted in the reduction of shortwave transmissions, as international broadcasters found ways to reach their audiences more easily.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However the United States Congress has introduced a bill to require all vehicles sold in the US to have an AM receiver to receive emergency broadcasts.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The FM broadcast band was established in 1941 in the United States, and at the time some suggested that the AM band would soon be eliminated.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In 1948, wide-band FM's inventor, Edwin H.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Since then the AM band's share of the audience has continued to decline.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In 1987, the elimination of the Fairness Doctrine requirement meant that talk shows, which were commonly carried by AM stations, could adopt a more focused presentation on controversial topics, without the distraction of having to provide airtime for any contrasting opinions.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In addition, satellite distribution made it possible for programs to be economically carried on a national scale.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The introduction of nationwide talk shows, most prominently Rush Limbaugh's beginning in 1988, was sometimes credited with "saving" AM radio.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However, these stations tended to attract older listeners who were of lesser interest to advertisers, and AM radio's audience share continued to erode.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In 1961, the FCC adopted a single standard for FM stereo transmissions, which was widely credited with enhancing FM's popularity.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Developing the technology for AM broadcasting in stereo was challenging due to the need to limit the transmissions to a 20 kHz bandwidth, while also making the transmissions backward compatible with existing non-stereo receivers.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In 1990, the FCC authorized an AM stereo standard developed by Magnavox, but two years later revised its decision to instead approve four competing implementations, saying it would "let the marketplace decide" which was best.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The lack of a common standard resulted in consumer confusion and increased the complexity and cost of producing AM stereo receivers.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In 1993, the FCC again revised its policy, by selecting C-QUAM as the sole AM stereo implementation.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] On June 8, 1988, an International Telecommunication Union (ITU)-sponsored conference held at Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, adopted provisions, effective July 1, 1990, to extend the upper end of the Region 2 AM broadcast band, by adding ten frequencies which spanned from 1610 kHz to 1700 kHz.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] At this time it was suggested that as many as 500 U.S. stations could be assigned to the new frequencies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] On April 12, 1990, the FCC voted to begin the process of populating the expanded band, with the main priority being the reduction of interference on the existing AM band, by transferring selected stations to the new frequencies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] It was now estimated that the expanded band could accommodate around 300 U.S. stations.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However, it turned out that the number of possible station reassignments was much lower, with a 2006 accounting reporting that, out of 4,758 licensed U.S.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] AM stations, only 56 were now operating on the expanded band.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] HD Radio is a digital audio broadcasting method developed by iBiquity.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In 2007, nighttime operation was also authorized.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The number of hybrid mode AM stations is not exactly known, because the FCC does not keep track of the stations employing the system, and some authorized stations have later turned it off.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] But as of 2020, the commission estimated that fewer than 250 AM stations were transmitting hybrid mode signals.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Despite the various actions, AM band audiences continued to contract, and the number of stations began to slowly decline.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] A 2009 FCC review reported that "The story of AM radio over the last 50 years has been a transition from being the dominant form of audio entertainment for all age groups to being almost non-existent to the youngest demographic groups.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Among persons aged 12–24, AM accounts for only 4% of listening, while FM accounts for 96%.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Among persons aged 25–34, AM accounts for only 9% of listening, while FM accounts for 91%.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In 2009, the FCC made a major regulatory change, when it adopted a policy allowing AM stations to simulcast over FM translator stations.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Translators had previously been available only to FM broadcasters, in order to increase coverage in fringe areas.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Their assignment for use by AM stations was intended to approximate the station's daytime coverage, which in cases where the stations reduced power at night, often resulted in expanded nighttime coverage.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Although the translator stations are not permitted to originate programming when the "primary" AM station is broadcasting, they are permitted to do so during nighttime hours for AM stations licensed for daytime-only operation.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Prior to the adoption of the new policy, as of March 18, 2009, the FCC had issued 215 Special Temporary Authority grants for FM translators relaying AM stations.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] After creation of the new policy, by 2011, there were approximately 500 in operation, and as of 2020, approximately 2,800 of the 4,570 licensed AM stations were rebroadcasting on one or more FM translators.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In 2009, the FCC stated that "We do not intend to allow these cross-service translators to be used as surrogates for FM stations".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However, based on station slogans, especially in the case of recently adopted musical formats, in most cases the expectation is that listeners will primarily be tuning into the FM signal rather than the nominally "primary" AM station.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] A 2020 review noted that "for many owners, keeping their AM stations on the air now is pretty much just about retaining their FM translator footprint rather than keeping the AM on the air on its own merits".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In 2018, the FCC, led by then-Commission Chairman Ajit Pai, proposed greatly reducing signal protection for 50 kW Class A "clear channel" stations.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] This would allow co-channel secondary stations to operate with higher powers, especially at night.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] However, the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) expressed concerns that this would reduce the effectiveness of emergency communications.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] In May 2023, a bipartisan group of lawmakers in the United States introduced legislation making it illegal for automakers to eliminate AM radio from their cars.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The lawmakers argue that AM radio is an important tool for public safety due to being a component of the Emergency Alert System (EAS).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] Some automakers have been eliminating AM radio from their electric vehicles (EVs) due to interference from the electric motors, but the lawmakers argue that this is a safety risk and that car owners should have access to AM radio regardless of the type of vehicle they drive.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] The proposed legislation would require all new vehicles to include AM radio at no additional charge, and it would also require automakers that have already eliminated AM radio to inform customers of alternatives.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p01] DRM30 is another standard to broadcast on the AM bands, with implementation in India and China, among other countries.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] AM radio technology is simpler than later transmission systems.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] An AM receiver detects amplitude variations in the radio waves at a particular frequency, then amplifies changes in the signal voltage to operate a loudspeaker or earphone.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] In large urban centers, AM radio signals can be severely disrupted by metal structures and tall buildings.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] As a result, AM radio tends to do best in areas where FM frequencies are in short supply, or in thinly populated or mountainous areas where FM coverage is poor.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] Great care must be taken to avoid mutual interference between stations operating on the same frequency.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] In general, an AM transmission needs to be about 20 times stronger than an interfering signal to avoid a reduction in quality, in contrast to FM signals, where the "capture effect" means that the dominant signal needs to only be about twice as strong as the interfering one.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] To allow room for more stations on the mediumwave broadcast band in the United States, in June 1989, the FCC adopted a National Radio Systems Committee (NRSC) standard that limited maximum transmitted audio bandwidth to 10.2 kHz, limiting occupied bandwidth to 20.4 kHz.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] The former audio limitation was 15 kHz resulting in bandwidth of 30 kHz.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] Another common limitation on AM fidelity is the result of receiver design, although some efforts have been made to improve this, notably through the AMAX standards adopted in the United States.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] AM broadcasts are used on several frequency bands.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] The allocation of these bands is governed by the ITU's Radio Regulations and, on the national level, by each country's telecommunications administration (the FCC in the U.S., for example) subject to international agreements.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] The frequency ranges given here are those that are allocated to stations.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] Because of the bandwidth taken up by the sidebands, the range allocated for the band as a whole is usually about 5 kHz wider on either side.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] Most of the earliest broadcasting experiments took place on longwave frequencies; however, complaints about interference from existing services, particularly the military, led to most broadcasting moving to higher frequencies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] Most broadcast services use AM transmissions, although some use a modified version of AM such as Single-sideband modulation (SSB) or an AM-compatible version of SSB such as "SSB with carrier reinserted".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] Beginning in the mid-1930s, the United States evaluated options for the establishment of broadcasting stations using much higher transmitting frequencies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] In October 1937, the FCC announced a second band of AM stations, consisting of 75 channels spanning from 41.02 to 43.98 MHz, which were informally called *Apex*.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] The 40 kHz spacing between adjacent frequencies was four times that of the 10 kHz spacing used on the standard AM broadcast band, which reduced adjacent-frequency interference, and provided more bandwidth for high-fidelity programming.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] However, this band was eliminated effective on January 1, 1941, after the FCC determined that establishing a band of FM stations was preferable.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] Beginning in the mid-1930s, starting with "The Brown Network" at Brown University in Providence, Rhode Island, a very low power broadcasting method known as carrier current was developed, and mostly adopted on U.S. college campuses.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] In this approach AM broadcast signals are distributed over electric power lines, which radiate a signal receivable at a short distance from the lines.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] In Switzerland a system known as "wire broadcasting" (*Telefonrundspruch* in German) transmitted AM signals over telephone lines in the longwave band until 1998, when it was shut down.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] In the UK, Rediffusion was an early pioneer of AM radio cable distribution.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] Hybrid digital broadcast systems, which combine (mono analog) AM transmission with digital sidebands, have started to be used around the world.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] In the United States, iBiquity's proprietary HD Radio has been adopted and approved by the FCC for medium wave transmissions, while Digital Radio Mondiale is a more open effort often used on the shortwave bands, and can be used alongside many AM broadcasts.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] Both of these standards are capable of broadcasting audio of significantly greater fidelity than that of standard AM with current bandwidth limitations, and a theoretical frequency response of 0–16 kHz, in addition to stereo sound and text data.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] Some microbroadcasters, especially those in the United States operating under the FCC's Part 15 rules, and pirate radio operators on mediumwave and shortwave, achieve greater range than possible on the FM band.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] On mediumwave these stations often transmit on 1610 kHz to 1710 kHz.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/am-radio-p02] Microbroadcasting and pirate radio have generally been supplanted by streaming audio on the Internet, but some schools and hobbyists still use LPAM transmissions.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] The airline provides scheduled passenger services from domestic French airports to points in North Africa including Algeria.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] The airline also operates transatlantic passenger services, on behalf of Air Saint-Pierre to the French overseas territory of Saint Pierre and Miquelon, off the coast of Newfoundland, Canada.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] Additionally, ASL Airlines France operates charter passenger flights throughout Europe for leading European tour operators and brokers.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] ASL Aviation Holdings DAC, the parent company of ASL Airlines Ireland, is headquartered in Swords, County Dublin, Ireland.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] The airline's roots go back to "Companie Générale Aéropostale" which in 1927 pioneered mail transport between Europe, Africa and South America employing famous pilots like Jean Mermoz and Antoine de Saint-Exupéry.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] The company was dissolved in 1932 and was then merged with other airlines to form Air France.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] After WWII the company was re-estabilished as an Air France subsidiary of from 1947 to 1991, operating as **Société d'Exploitation Aéropostale** but with no aircraft of its own.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] A similar activity was set up in 1987 when Air Inter and EAS Europe Airlines jointly founded **Intercargo Service** to fly cargo runs with all-cargo Vickers Vanguard made available by the latter parent.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] The air carrier was reformed in April 1990 with **ICS-Inter Ciel Service** brand and over the following year **Aéropostale** (or **L'Aéropostale**) corporate name was adopted.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] As an Air France Group 50%-owned subsidiary the company grew rapidly and new aircraft gradually entered the fleet: Airbus A300, Boeing 727, Boeing 737, most of them in all-cargo internal configuration.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] Night operations were exclusively on La Poste behalf while during the day the airline flew scheduled and charter flights on Air France behalf.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] Regional flights were added thanks to the use of ATR 72 tuboprops.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] When La Poste took over full ownership the airline corporate name was changed to **Europe Airpost** on 1 December 2000.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] Consequently all flight activities were exclusively operated for the French national postal service.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] As of March 2007 The company had 400 employees.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] A proposed sale to Imperial Holdings of South Africa in February 2007 kwas cancelled but the sale to Air Contractors of Dublin Ireland (parially owned by Imperial Holdings) was agreed in February 2008.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] On March 14, 2008, ASL Aviation Holdings DAC officially acquired the airline.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] The aircraft kept the former livery and call sign.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] On June 4, 2015, the parent company ASL Aviation Holdings DAC announced that the airline would be renamed **ASL Airlines France**.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] In June 2021, at the Paris Air Show, ASL Aviation Holdings DAC announced an order with Boeing for up to 20 737-800 Boeing Converted Freighter (BCF) aircraft - 10 firm orders and 10 options.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] This was extended to an additional 20 737-800(BCF) in March 2022 for a total of 40 orders including options.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/asl-airlines-france] Eleven aircraft to operate for ASL Airlines Belgium, ASL Airlines France, ASL Airlines Ireland and ASL joint venture, K-Mile Asia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/pm] As of June 2021, there are more than 7000 registered .pm domains.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/pm] Since 1 January 2021, British citizens have not been able to register .pm domains.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/pm] However, as AFNIC is unable to apply policies retroactively, it is allowing all registrations pre-Brexit to continue, with renewal permitted.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Saint Pierre and Miquelon is an overseas country and territory (OCT) of the European Union, although not an integral part of it.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] It is neither part of the Schengen area, nor of the European customs territory.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] On the other hand, the euro is the official currency in Saint Pierre and Miquelon, and its inhabitants have European Union citizenship.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The territory is also part of the Regional Joint Cooperation Commission (Atlantic Canada Cooperation), the Halifax Search and Rescue Region and the Northwest Atlantic Fisheries Organization.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Lawrence near the entrance of Fortune Bay, which extends into the southwestern coast of Newfoundland, near the Grand Banks of Newfoundland.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Pierre is 19 kilometres (10+1⁄2 nautical miles) from Point May on the Burin Peninsula of Newfoundland and 3,819 kilometres (2,373 mi) from Brest, the nearest city in Metropolitan France.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The tiny Canadian Green Island lies 10 kilometres (5+1⁄2 nmi) east of Saint Pierre, roughly halfway to Point May.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] It has been claimed that the name *Miquelon* is a Basque form of Michael; *Mikel* and *Mikels* are usually named *Mikelon* in the Basque Country.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Therefore, from *Mikelon*, it may have been written in the French way with a *qu* instead of a *k*.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The Basque Country is divided between Spain and France, and most Basques live south of the border.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] As such, Miquelon may have been influenced by the Spanish name *Miguelón*, an augmentative form of Miguel meaning "big Michael".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The adjoined island's name of "Langlade" is said to be an adaptation of *l'île à l'Anglais* (Englishman's Island).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Archaeological evidence indicates that indigenous peoples of Canada, such as the Beothuk, visited Saint Pierre and Miquelon.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] However, there is no evidence they settled on the islands permanently.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] On 21 October 1520, the Portuguese explorer João Álvares Fagundes landed on the islands and named the island group they were part of the "Eleven Thousand Virgins", as the day marked the feast day of Saint Ursula and her virgin companions.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 1536, the French explorer Jacques Cartier claimed the islands as a possession of France.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Though already frequented by the Mi'kmaq and by Basque and Breton fishermen, the islands were not permanently settled until the end of the 17th century: four permanent inhabitants were counted in 1670, and 22 in 1691.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 1670, during Jean Talon's second tenure as Intendant of New France, a French officer annexed the islands after he discovered 12 French fishermen encamped there, naming them Saint Pierre and Miquelon.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] During King William's War and Queen Anne's War, English forces launched multiple attacks against French colonial settlements on the islands, and by the early 18th century French colonists had abandoned Saint Pierre and Miquelon all together.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In the 1713 Peace of Utrecht, which ended the War of the Spanish Succession, France ceded the islands to Britain.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The British renamed the island of Saint Pierre to Saint Peter, and small numbers of colonists from Britain and British America began to settle on the islands.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The 1763 Treaty of Paris, which ended the Seven Years' War, resulted in the French ceding all of New France to Britain and Spain, though the British granted fishing rights to French fishermen along the Newfoundland coast and returned Saint Pierre and Miquelon to France.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 1778, after France joined the American Revolutionary War against Britain, British forces under Vice-admiral John Montagu occupied Saint Pierre and Miquelon, burning all French settlements on the islands and deporting their inhabitants back to France.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 1793, another British force under Captain William Affleck occupied the islands during the War of the First Coalition; in the following year, the island's French colonists were deported and a British colony was established on Saint Pierre.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] During the 1796 Newfoundland expedition, the nascent British colony was evacuated after the appearance of French Navy squadron under Counter-admiral Joseph de Richery, which proceeded to burn the abandoned settlement.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The 1802 Treaty of Amiens brought the islands back under French control, only for Britain to retake them after Napoleonic Wars began the following year.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] They were returned to France once more under the 1814 Treaty of Paris, though the British briefly occupied the islands during the Hundred Days in 1815.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] When the French returned to the islands in 1816, they found that all of its colonial settlements had been destroyed or fallen into ruin.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The islands were gradually resettled by Breton, Norman and Basque settlers, joined by various other peoples, particularly from Newfoundland.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The colony's economy did not recover for another 35 years.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 1903, the colony toyed with the idea of joining the United States; however, nothing came of the idea.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] During the early 1910s, the colony suffered economic hardship as a result of unprofitable fisheries, and large numbers of its inhabitants emigrated to Nova Scotia and Quebec.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The draft imposed by French authorities on all male inhabitants of conscription age after the outbreak of World War I in 1914 crippled the fisheries, as their catch could not be processed by the older men or the women and children.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] About 400 men from the colony served in the French Armed Forces during the war, 100 of whom died.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The increase in the adoption of steam fishing trawlers in the fisheries also contributed to the reduction in employment opportunities.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Smuggling had always been an important economic activity in the islands; however, it became especially prominent in the 1920s with the institution of prohibition in the United States from January 1920 onwards.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 1931, the archipelago was reported by *The New York Times* to have imported 1,815,271 U.S. gallons (1,511,529 imperial gallons; 6,871,550 liters) of whisky from Canada in 12 months, most of which was smuggled into the United States.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The end of prohibition in 1933 plunged the islands once more into economic depression.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] During World War II, despite opposition from Canada, Britain, and the United States, the Free French Forces seized the islands from Vichy France, to which the colony's administrator Gilbert de Bournat had pledged its allegiance, on 24 December 1941.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In referendums on both islands, the population endorsed Free France's takeover by over 98%.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The colony became a French overseas territory in 1946.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The archipelago became an overseas department on 19 July 1976, before acquiring the status of territorial collectivity on 11 June 1985, thus withdrawing from the European Communities.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Since March 2003, Saint Pierre and Miquelon has been an overseas collectivity with a special status.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The archipelago has two communes: Saint-Pierre and Miquelon-Langlade.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] A third commune, Isle-aux-Marins, existed until 1945, when it was absorbed by the municipality of Saint-Pierre.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The inhabitants possess French citizenship and suffrage.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Saint Pierre and Miquelon sends a senator and a deputy to the National Assembly of France in Paris and enjoys a degree of autonomy concerning taxes, customs, and excise.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] France appoints the prefect of Saint Pierre and Miquelon, who represents the national government in the territory.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The prefect is in charge of national interests, law enforcement, public order, and, under the conditions set by the statute of 1985, administrative control.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Since 21 August 2023, the prefect has been Bruno André.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The local legislative body, the Territorial Council (French: *Conseil territorial*), has 19 members: four councillors from Miquelon-Langlade and 15 from Saint-Pierre.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The President of the Territorial Council is the head of a delegation of "France in the name of Saint Pierre and Miquelon" for international events such as the annual meetings of NAFO and ICCAT.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] France is responsible for the defence of the islands.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The French Navy deploys the ex-trawler *Fulmar* in the territory for operations in both territorial and regional waters.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Law enforcement in Saint Pierre and Miquelon is the responsibility of a branch of the French Gendarmerie Nationale; there are two police stations in the archipelago.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] France claimed a 200-nautical-mile (370 km; 230 mi) exclusive economic zone for Saint-Pierre and Miquelon.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Further, in August 1983, the naval ship *Lieutenant de vaisseau Le Hénaff* and the seismic ship *Lucien Beaufort* were sent to explore for oil in the disputed zone.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In addition to the potential oil reserves, cod fishing rights on the Grand Banks of Newfoundland were at stake in the dispute.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In the late 1980s, indications of declining fish stocks began to raise serious concern over the depletion of the fishery.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 1992, an arbitration panel awarded the islands an exclusive economic zone of 12,348 square kilometres (4,768 sq mi) to settle a longstanding territorial dispute with Canada, although it represents only 25% of what France had sought.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The 1992 decision fixed the maritime boundaries between Canada and the islands, but did not demarcate the continental shelf.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Located off the western end of the Newfoundland's Burin Peninsula, the archipelago of Saint Pierre and Miquelon comprises eight islands, totalling 242 square kilometres (93 mi2), of which only two are inhabited.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The islands are bare and rocky, with steep coasts, and only a thin layer of peat to soften the hard landscape.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The islands, like Newfoundland, are geologically part of the northeastern end of the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] A third, formerly inhabited island, *Isle-aux-Marins*, was known as *Île-aux-Chiens* until 1931.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] It is located a short distance from the port of Saint-Pierre, and has been uninhabited since 1963.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The other main islands are *Grand Colombier*, *Île aux Vainqueurs*, and *Île aux Pigeons*.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Seals and other wildlife can be found in the Grand Barachois Lagoon of Miquelon.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Every spring, whales migrating to Greenland are visible off the coasts of Saint-Pierre and Miquelon.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Trilobite fossils have been found on Langlade.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The stone pillars off the island coasts called "L'anse aux Soldats" eroded away and disappeared in the 1970s.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The rocky islands are barren, except for scrubby yews and junipers and thin volcanic soil.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The forest cover of the hills, except in parts of Langlade, had been removed for fuel long ago.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In spite of being located at a similar latitude to the Bay of Biscay, the archipelago is characterized by a cold borderline humid continental/subarctic climate, under the influence of polar air masses and the cold Labrador Current.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The mild winters for being a subarctic climate also means it has influences of subpolar oceanic climate, thus being at the confluence of three climatic types.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The February mean is just below the −3 °C (27 °F) isotherm for that classification.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Typical maritime seasonal lag is also strong with September being warmer than June and March being colder than December.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The average temperature is 5.3 °C (41.5 °F), with a temperature range of 19 °C (35 °F) between the warmest (15.7 °C (60.3 °F) in August) and coldest months (−3.6 °C (25.5 °F) in February).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Precipitation is abundant (1,312 mm or 51.7 in per year) and regular (146 days per year), falling as snow and rain.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Because of its location at the confluence of the cold waters of the Labrador Current and the warm waters of the Gulf Stream, the archipelago is also crossed a hundred days a year by fog banks, mainly in June and July.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Two other climatic elements are remarkable: the extremely variable winds and haze during the spring to early summer.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The economy of the islands, due to their location, has been dependent on fishing and servicing fishing fleets operating off the coast of Newfoundland.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The economy has been declining, however, due to disputes with Canada over fishing quotas and a decline in the number of ships stopping at the islands.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 1992 an arbitration panel awarded the islands an exclusive economic zone of 12,348 square kilometres (4,768 sq mi) to settle a longstanding territorial dispute with Canada, although it represents only 25 percent of what France had sought.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The islands are heavily subsidized by France, which benefits the standard of living.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The government hopes an expansion of tourism will boost economic prospects, and test drilling for oil may pave the way for development of the energy sector.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The climate and the small amount of available land militate against activities such as farming and livestock raising (weather conditions are severe, confining the growing season to a few weeks, and the soil contains significant peat and clay and is largely infertile).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Since 1992 the economy has been in steep decline, following the depletion of fish stocks due to overfishing, the limitation of fishing areas and the ban imposed on all cod fishing by the Canadian Government.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The labour market is characterized by high seasonality, due to climatic hazards.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Traditionally, the inhabitants suspended all outdoor activities (construction, agriculture, etc.) between December and April.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 1999, the unemployment rate was 12.8%, and a third of the employed worked in the public sector.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The employment situation was worsened by the complete cessation of deep-sea fishing, the traditional occupation of the islanders, as the unemployment rate in 1990 was lower at 9.5%.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The unemployment for 2010 shows a decrease from 2009, from 7.7% to 7.1%.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Exports are very low (5.1% of GDP) while imports are significant (49.1% of GDP).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 2023, the unemployment rate in Saint-Pierre-et-Miquelon was 2.9%.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] About 70% of the islands' supplies are imported from Canada or from other parts of France via Nova Scotia.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The rise in unemployment has been countered by state financial aid for the retraining of businesses and individuals.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The construction of the airport in 1999 helped sustain activity in the construction industry and public works.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Fish farming, crab fishing and agriculture are being developed to diversify the local economy.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The future of Saint Pierre and Miquelon rests on tourism, fisheries and aquaculture.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Explorations are under way to exploit deposits of oil and gas.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Tourism benefits from the proximity to similar tourist areas of Canada.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Distribution, public service, care, minor wholesale, retail and crafts are notable in the business sector.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Tourism is increasingly important and the territory capitalises on its image as "*France in North America*".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] There are, as of mid-2024, six hotels on Saint-Pierre as well as B&Bs and Airbnb rentals on both main islands.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] As of mid-2024, there are 13 restaurants and bistros on Saint-Pierre and one on Île aux Marins; further, the islands' tourism bureau promotes their authentic French cuisine as well as other cuisines.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The euro has been the official currency in Saint Pierre and Miquelon since 1 January 1999, while the euro coins and banknotes were introduced on 1 January 2002, in tandem with Metropolitan France.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Before 1890, Mexican dubloons and Canadian dollars both circulated on the islands.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Starting in 1889, these were supplemented with local franc banknotes from the Banque des Îles Saint-Pierre-et-Miquelon until the end of World War One.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 1945, the island started using the CFA franc, which otherwise was used by the French colonies in Africa.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] CFA banknotes issued by the Caisse Centrale de la France d'Outre-Mer stamped with the text "Saint Pierre et Miquelon".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 1973, these were replaced with the ("regular") new French franc, which had been in use in Metropolitan France since 1960, equal to 100 pre-1960 French francs.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The Institut d'Émission des Départements d'Outre-Mer (IEDOM), the French public institution responsible for issuing currency in the overseas territories that used the French franc and later the euro on behalf of the Bank of France, has had an agency in Saint Pierre since 1978.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Most businesses accept Canadian dollars (CAD), at a rate below the interbank exchange rate; prices in euros and change would be given in that currency.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The islands have issued their own stamps from 1885 to the present, except for a period between 1 April 1978 and 3 February 1986 when French stamps not specific to Saint Pierre and Miquelon were used.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The total population of the islands at the March 2022 census was 5,819, of which 5,223 lived in Saint-Pierre and 596 in Miquelon-Langlade.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] At the time of the 1999 census, 76% of the population was born on the archipelago, while 16.1% were born in metropolitan France, a sharp increase from the 10.2% in 1990.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In the same census, less than 1% of the population reported being a foreign national.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The archipelago has a high emigration rate, especially among young adults, who often leave for their studies without returning afterwards.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Even at the time of the great prosperity of the cod fishery, the population growth had always been constrained by the geographic remoteness, harsh climate and infertile soils.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Ruins show that Indigenous American people visited the archipelago on fishing and hunting expeditions before it was settled by Europeans.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The inhabitants speak French; their customs and traditions are similar to those found in metropolitan France.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The French spoken on the archipelago is closer to Metropolitan French than to Canadian French and maintains a number of unique features.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Basque, formerly spoken in private settings by people of Basque ancestry, had disappeared from the islands by the late 1950s.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The population is overwhelmingly Christian, with the majority being Catholic.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The Vicariate Apostolic of Iles Saint-Pierre and Miquelon managed the local church until it was merged into the Diocese of La Rochelle and Saintes in 2018.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Every summer there is a Basque Festival, which has demonstrations of harri-jasotzaileak (stone heaving), aizkolaritza (lumberjack skills), and Basque pelota (more widely known in the Americas as frontón/jai alai).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The local cuisine is mostly based on seafood such as lobster, snow crab, mussels, and especially cod.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Street names are not commonly used on the islands.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Directions and locations are commonly given using nicknames and the names of nearby residents.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The only time the guillotine was used in North America was on Saint-Pierre in the late 19th century.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Joseph Néel was convicted of killing Mr Coupard on Île aux Chiens on 30 December 1888, and subsequently executed by guillotine on 24 August 1889.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The device had to be shipped from the French territory of Martinique and it did not arrive in working order.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] It was very difficult to get anyone to perform the execution; finally a recent immigrant was coaxed into doing the job.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] This event was the inspiration for the 2000 film *The Widow of Saint-Pierre*.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The guillotine is now in a museum in Saint-Pierre.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Ice hockey is very popular in Saint-Pierre and Miquelon, with local teams often competing in Newfoundland-based leagues.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Several players from the islands have played on French and Canadian club teams, and participated on the France men's national ice hockey team.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 2008, Saint-Pierre and Miquelon played an exhibition match against the French national team and lost 6–8.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The territory has not fielded a national side since then.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Saint Pierre and Miquelon has a domestic football league comprising three teams.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Starting in 2018, local clubs have competed in France's domestic knockout cup, the Coupe de France.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The territory also has a national team, but it is presently not a member of FIFA or CONCACAF.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Saint-Pierre and Miquelon has 114 km (71 mi) of highways plus 45 km (28 mi) of unpaved roads.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Its only major harbour is at Saint-Pierre although there is a smaller harbour at Miquelon.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The collectivity has no merchant marine but has two airports; the runway at Saint-Pierre Airport is 1,800 metres (5,910 ft) long, and at Miquelon Airport, 1,000 metres (3,280 ft).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Ferry services connect the islands with each other and with Fortune on Newfoundland in Canada, 45 km away; crossings take 90 minutes.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Saint Pierre and Miquelon no longer have any functioning railways.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Ferry services operated by SPM Ferries connect Saint Pierre with Miquelon town and Langlade, and both Saint Pierre and Miquelon towns with the port of Fortune on Newfoundland in Canada.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In the summer, additional services operate between St Pierre and Langlade and between Miquelon and Fortune.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] SPM Ferries's Nordet and Suroît ferries can transport up to 188 passengers and 18 vehicles each.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] *Jeune France* is a smaller ferry serving seasonal local service between St.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The ship arrived in 2012 replacing *Saint-George XII*, and currently is used for tours.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Several cruise ship lines visit Saint-Pierre.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] They dock 2 km northeast of downtown, near the end of the coastal road.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Boats also provide access to Ile aux Marins.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Between 2005 and 2009, Atlantic Jet provided a ferry service to the islands from Canada, operated privately by SPM Express SA.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] It was replaced by the Arethusa, but the service was terminated in 2010 when the island opted to form a government-run ferry service.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Due to COVID-19 restrictions, services to Fortune were suspended between March 2020 and August 2021.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] There are two airports on the islands: Saint-Pierre Pointe-Blanche Airport (IATA: **FSP**, ICAO: **LFVP**) and Miquelon Airport (IATA: **MQC**, ICAO: **LFVM**).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] For many years there was no direct air link between Saint Pierre and mainland France, but in summer 2018, Air Saint-Pierre began direct flights to and from Paris during the summer.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] There are other connections to mainland France: WestJet provides seasonal flights to Paris-CDG from both Halifax and St.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In the past, Saint Pierre and Miquelon used only standard French vehicle registration plates, rather than plates in the format of six inches (150 mm) high by twelve inches (300 mm) wide used by most other jurisdictions in North America.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] More recently however, American vehicles with North American plates are becoming more common; this has increased since the new car ferry service to Canada began in 2021.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The islands do not follow the standard French numbering system.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Until 1952, cars were simply numbered from 1 onwards, without any code to identify them as being from Saint Pierre and Miquelon.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Beginning in 1952, they had serial numbers followed by the letters SPM; for example, 9287 SPM.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Since 2000, all numbers have begun with the letters SPM followed by a serial number and serial letter, e.g.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Road signs are in French and are European influenced.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Saint-Pierre and Miquelon have four radio stations; all stations operate on the FM band, with the last stations converted from the AM band in 2004.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Three of the stations are on Saint-Pierre, two of which are owned by La Première, along with one La Première station on Miquelon.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] At night, these stations broadcast France Inter or France Info.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The other station (Radio Atlantique) is an affiliate of Radio France Internationale.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The archipelago is linked to North America and Europe by satellite communications for telephone and television service.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The archipelago is also home to the Saint Pierre et Miquelon *Galileo Sensor Station* (GSS), operated by the European Union and its space programme agency (EUSPA) for the European satellite positioning systems *Galileo* and EGNOS.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] It is the only *Galileo* installation in North America.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] On the other hand, another EGNOS station is located in Moncton, Canada; however, this is due to be replaced by the facilities in Saint Pierre et Miquelon.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The department of Saint-Pierre and Miquelon is served by one television station: Saint Pierre and Miquelon La Première (call sign FQN) on Channel 1.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Before the conversion to the DVB-T standard for digital television broadcasts on 29 November 2011, Saint-Pierre and Miquelon used the French analog SECAM-K1 standard.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Further, the local telecommunications provider (SPM Telecom) carried many North American television stations and cable channels; the channels were converted from North America's analog NTSC standard.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In addition, Saint-Pierre-et-Miquelon La Première was carried on Shaw Direct satellite and most digital cable services in Canada, converted to NTSC.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] SPM Telecom is also the department's main internet service provider.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Its internet service being named *Cheznoo;* this is a play on "chez-nous," French for "our place." SPM Telecom also offers cellular phone and mobile phone service (for phones that adhere to the GSM standard).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] SPM Telecom uses the GSM 900 MHz band, which is different from the GSM 850 MHz and 1900 MHz bands used in the rest of North America.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The islands are a well-known separate country-level entity among many radio amateurs; it is identifiable with ITU prefix "FP".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Those visiting, mainly from the US, activate Saint-Pierre and Miquelon every year on amateur frequencies.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Amateurs collect (records of) contacts with these stations for Islands on the Air and DX Century Club awards; the Atlantic coast gives great takeoff for shortwaves.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] A few kilometres away is Signal Hill, St.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] John's which first communicated across the Atlantic, namely with Marconi's Poldhu Wireless Station in England.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] SPM Telecom publishes local news online at the *Cheznoo* web portal.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Other publications include the magazine "Mathurin".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The Saint Pierre and Miquelon *La Première* television channel provides a news program every evening at 8pm, called "*Le Journal*".
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The archipelago has four primary schools (Sainte Odile, Henriette Bonin, Feu Rouge, les Quatre-Temps), one middle school (Collège Saint-Christophe) with an annex in Miquelon, one state (government) high school (Lycée-Collège d'État Émile Letournel) and one vocational high school.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Students who wish to further their studies after high school are granted access to scholarships to study overseas.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Most students go to metropolitan France; however, some go to Canada, mainly New Brunswick or Quebec.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Saint-Pierre has had a branch of Memorial University of Newfoundland, the Frecker Institute, since 1973.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Since 2001, Frecker had been operated by the local government in Saint Pierre and Miquelon, with support of the federal government of Canada and the provincial government of Newfoundland and Labrador.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Today, the Frecker Institute has been replaced by the Frecker Program.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] However, it is held within the building of the *Institut de langue française* Francoforum, which is now the only French-language institute offering university-level teaching on the island.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Saint-Pierre and Miquelon's health care system is entirely public and free.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] In 1994, France and Canada signed an agreement allowing the residents of the archipelago to be treated in St.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Pierre and Miquelon indicated that they would start looking for a new healthcare provider as recent rate increases by Eastern Health in Newfoundland were too expensive (increasing to $3.3 million in 2014 from $2.5 million in 2010).
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Halifax, Nova Scotia and Moncton, New Brunswick were mooted as possible locations.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Since 1985, Hôpital François Dunan provides basic care and emergency care for residents of both islands.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] The island's first hospital was military in 1904 and became a civilian facility in 1905.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] L'Hôpital-Hospice-Orphelinat opened in 1937.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Advance paediatric health needs are serviced through Janeway Children's Health and Rehabilitation Centre in St.
[src:saint-pierre-and-miquelon/saint-pierre-and-miquelon] Most are second-hand units from North America; however, St Pierre acquired an aerial ladder from France in 2016.
